text: I hate to be that guy, but this just looks like a balls to the wall action flick. The first Sicario was an actual compelling commentary on the nature of the Mexican drug war and the ethical implications that make this war more complicated and messy compared to say the war in the Middle East. It was kinda like a Syriana but for the drug war in Mexico.  It just so happens that Benicio Del Toro was a badass character in the film and had some really great action scenes. But that wasn't the MAIN focus of the film......Sicario didn't need a sequel and I feel like this is going to give people the wrong impression of what the first film was trying to achieve.

text: Mustache glasses guy is back! "Leave Fiji alone, terrorists!" That sardonic son-of-a-bitch looks like an insurance salesman, but he's equally as dangerous as Medellin.  He's knee-deep in shootouts and interrogations, but is completely detached emotionally.  He adds levity through observations and anecdotes, yet remains a mystery because his role is not completely defined, nor why he participates with teams he chooses.  Shadow figures like him are scary as hell when they're smart, efficient, and don't mind getting out first to engage with dangerous people.  I hope they go a bit further with his character and who he is because they could probably create a whole other movie around his tactical history and the stuff he's been involved in.  Brolin's character is easy to understand and there's no mystery there, he's really just a necessary CIA figure, but that mustache glasses guy, that dickhead goes around burying people, but we don't know how dirty his hands are, only that he's our government's tip of the spear.  A third Sicario could even be written as a prequel, covering when stache, Brolin, and Medellin first became acquainted so we know some of the history which created their personalities as effective killers.

text: Guys, don't tell me you didn't notice the best part: at 0:13, he says: "How would you define terrorism? The current definition is any individual or group that uses violence to achieve a political goal." Then the scene shows a prisoner or terrorist who is covered with a black hood. My first thought: torture. Even though Sicario and now Soldado are about terrorists such as the drug cartels, this is not the only thing the movies deal with. They show the other side of politics where the "good people" use torture to achieve a political goal. This is what I loved about Sicario and am looking forward to in Soldado. Sicario was by far one of the best movies I have ever seen. Del Toro was absolutely terrific and I was impressed by both Brolin and Blunt.

text: This looks alright, but.... Why? "Sicario" didn't need a sequel (or a saga). The mystery behind Alejandro and what his plans were after getting revenge was a good enough ending. How was the CIA going to handle the Colombian cartel? What happens to Kate? Does she stay on and continue hunting thr cartels? Who knows? And honestly... Who cares? This just ruins all of that.   But no, they had to make an action-packed sequel of a thriller. Without the main character of the first movie! So she's useless. Lame. None of these characters needed an expansion of their stories. Now it's going to turn into "Taken" and "The Transporter". No life. No substance.  Hard pass.

text: I really hope this movie sticks to the unconventional side of things like the first. It seems every movie like this nowadays has one character that needs to "do the right thing" and be the moral barometer. And as one can predict, the moral one always wins. But not in the first Sicario. I was pleasantly surprised when the "bad guys" won. Much more realistic and unpredictable. So I really really hope they keep to the brutal truth of how the real-world is and how it operates (ie. the good/moral characters don't always prevail).
